@@eThe Forest of Confusion: Containment and Its Costs@@N

@@yFrom the Garden Ledger, Ecological Governance Studies@@N
@@dPresented at the Ember Warden Seasonal Review@@N

North of @@yKiess@@N lies a forest where travelers are @@rmisled by
intent@@N. Landmarks repeat. Bells sound from impossible directions.
The Garden Ledger Clerks study this place because it contains
@@ytwo lessons@@N, and most observers only learn one.

The first lesson concerns @@gcontainment@@N. The @@rconfusion mists@@N
were deliberately engineered by druids to contain @@lcrystal
matrices@@N the @@WSpirebound Conclave@@N embedded in the forest's root
systems and then @@rabandoned@@N. The druids worked @@gwith@@N the
forest's own intelligence -- the root network's ecological responses
-- to create a living quarantine that adapted as the threat shifted.

This is @@gbeautiful@@N. The Bloom Pavilion recognizes the same
principle that underlies the @@ySouthward Compact@@N: that living
systems, respected and cooperated with, can accomplish what
imposed order @@rcannot@@N. The druids understood the forest was
a @@gpartner@@N, not a resource.

The second lesson is harder. The Conclave's @@lresonance crystals@@N
were the original wound -- instruments of control embedded in a
living system by an institution that collapsed without retrieving
them. @@rImposed order on a living system, abandoned when the
imposers lost interest.@@N The Ember Wardens see this the way they
see Midgaard's @@rresettlement policies@@N: an institution reshaping
a living community for its own purposes, then walking away.

The druids maintained containment for centuries. Then they died --
@@dnot dramatically, but demographically@@N. Without maintenance, the
mists diffused and what was purposeful became @@rdangerous@@N. The
Garden Ledger Clerks recognize this: @@yeven beautiful cooperation
requires people to sustain it@@N.

Rakuen knows this intimately. Our waterworks were @@gbeautiful@@N
when the founding generation maintained them. When the Ash-and-Iron
killed the orchards and the next generation could not sustain
what the first had built, our systems drifted too.

The @@gTreants@@N guard as sentinels, bearing both healthy bark and
blight scarring. The @@eCentaurs@@N maintain armed neutrality, their
oral tradition preserving the forest before the mists. Communities
that @@gpersist@@N within damage, adapting without surrendering.

Rakuen empathizes. We too persist within damage. The Cracked
Promise Stones still stand. The Bloom Pavilion's ivy still grows.
The mists drift, and so do we, but @@gwe have not stopped
tending what remains@@N.
